1. Introduction
Diabetes mellitus (DM) is a chronic metabolic disorder syndrome,
which is characterized by hyperglycemia and insulin resistance.
According to International Diabetes Federation, there were 425
million diabetics in 2017 and will be 700 million diabetics in 2045
(IDF, 2017). Particularly, type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM) accounts for
90 % of all diabetics. Substantial evidences indicate that DM leads to a
variety of complications, among which diabetes-associated cognitive
impairment affects individuals worldwide.1,2 About 60e70 % pa-
tients with DM has mild or moderate cognitive impairment,3 which
manifests in slower in learning and memory, reasoning ability, a lack
of attention and other symptoms.4 Epidemiological evidence shows
DM is associated with a higher risk of dementia and Alzheimer's
disease (AD) and has a 2e3 times increase in relative risk of AD.5
Interestingly, amyloid b protein (Ab) deposition and neuroﬁbrillary
tangles consisting of hyperphosphorylated tau protein, which are
two major pathological hallmarks in AD, are more likely to be
pathological hallmarks for diabetes-associated cognitive dysfunc-
tion.6 Notably, some researchers have indicated the failure of Ab
clearance might impair the insulin pathway, increasing Ab accu-
mulation in T2DM patients.7 However, the mechanisms underlying
the diabetes-associated cognitive dysfunction have not been clearly
identiﬁed, and few effective clinical interventions are available to
prevent the disease.
Glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) is a 30-amino acid endogenous
incretin hormone, which is released by small intestinal L-cells after
meal to perform metabolic functions (e.g. modulating glucose ho-
meostasis by potentiating glucose-dependent insulin secretion
in vivo). GLP-1 plays an important role in physiology by binding to
GLP-1 receptor (GLP-1R).8,9 Researchers show that GLP-1R is found
in neurons of rodents and human brains. And GLP-1 can cross the
bloodebrain barrier (BBB) to promote synaptic formation, neuro-
genesis and reduce chronic inﬂammatory response of neuron
cells.8,10,11 In addition, GLP-1 provides neuroprotection via regulating
