Journal of Pharmacological Sciences 147 (2021) 234e244
Ca2þ homeostasis, reducing neuronal apoptosis, modulating Ab
clearance, improving the mitochondrial dysfunction and amelio-
rating the autophagy, thereby improving the cognitive function.12e15
Liraglutide is a long-acting analog of GLP-1 and binds to GLP-1R to
exhibit neuroprotective effects.16 But the mechanisms underlying
liraglutide's affecting diabetes-associated
cognitive
impairment
remain to be clariﬁed.
Autophagy is characterized by degradation of intracellular and
damaged organelles and helps maintain cellular homeostasis. In
most cases, autophagy plays a role in preventing and delaying cell
death, but autophagic accumulation leads to cell death. Notably, the
defect of autophagic ﬂux is thought to be common to many
neurodegenerative disorders, including AD, amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis and Parkinson's disease (PD).17 Moreover, the defected
autophagic ﬂux in central nervous system causes the accumulation
of damaged proteins and organelles, indicating an essential role of
autophagy in neurodegeneration. T2DM is also associated with the
defection of autophagic ﬂux, which could be the pathogenesis of
diabetes-associated cognitive impairment. Therefore, targeting to
autophagic ﬂux may be neuroprotective in diabetes-associated
cognitive impairment.18,19
Recently, liraglutide has been found to attenuate the impaired
learning and memory, synaptic plasticity, decrease hippocampal
neuronal
loss,
reduce
Ab
oligomer
levels
and
tau
hyper-
phosphorylation, and promote neurogenesis in AD mice.20,21 Re-
searchers also indicate liraglutide ameliorates cognitive decline by
promoting autophagy in diabetic mice.15,22 But the speciﬁc mech-
anism by which liraglutide regulates autophagic ﬂux is still unclear.
Therefore, in this study, we explore whether liraglutide can
ameliorate the impaired autophagic ﬂux by reducing the accumu-
lation of autophagosomes and increasing the fusion of autopha-
gosome and lysosome in vivo and vitro. To better understand the
potential mechanisms underlying diabetic-associated cognitive
impairment, high glucose (HG)-injured rat primary cortical neu-
rons and T2DM mice (fed with high fat diet combined with strep-
tozotocin (STZ)) with cognitive deﬁcit were used in our study.
2. Materials and methods
2.1. The establishment of type 2 diabetes (T2DM) model and drug
administration
All animal were used in accordance with the National Institutes
of Health Guide for Care and Use of Laboratory Animals. Six-week-
old healthy male C57BL/6 mice weighting 18e22 g were purchased
from Medical Experimental Animal Center of Xi'an Jiaotong
University Health Science Center. All the mice were housed in a
consistent temperature (21 ± 2 C), humidity (40%e60 %), and light
cycle (12 h/12 h light/dark) environment with free access to food
and water.
After 1 week of acclimatization, mice were randomly divided
into normal control group (n ¼ 8, fed with an ordinary diet until the
end of the experiment) and high-fat diet (HFD) group (n ¼ 20, fed
with HFD containing 20 % protein, 20 % carbohydrate, 60 % fat until
the end of the experiment) (Xietong Organism, Jiangsu, China).
After 8 weeks of ordinary or high-fat diet administration, HFD mice
were received intraperitoneal (i.p.) injection of STZ at a dose of
60 mg/kg (SigmaeAldrich, USA) for consecutive 3 days after fasted
for 12 h to induce diabetes. Control mice (n ¼ 8) were received an
intraperitoneal injection of equivalent volume of citrate buffer.
After 3 days of STZ injection, fasting blood glucose (FBG) levels were
determined with a blood glucometer after fasted for 6 h by snipping
the tails. The mice with a FBG level in the range of 15e25 mmol/L
were considered as T2DM model. The success rate was 80 %. Then
the HFD mice (n ¼ 16) were randomly divided into 2 groups as
follows: (1) T2DM group (n ¼ 8), in which the mice were received
subcutaneous injection of equivalent volume of normal saline for 6
weeks; (2) Liraglutide group (n ¼ 8), in which the mice were
received subcutaneous injection of liraglutide (Novo Alle, DK-2880
Bagsvaerd, Denmark) at a dose of 300 mg/kg/day for 6 weeks. The
mice in the normal control group were received subcutaneous in-
jection of equivalent volume of normal saline for 6 weeks. The body
weight (BW) and FBG levels were determined in each week. When
the Morris water maze (MWM) tests were ﬁnished, all the mice
were deeply anesthetized with sodium pentobarbital (40 mg/kg).
Three of 8 mice in each group were used to harvest the brains for
morphologic analysis. Others were used for protein analysis. For
morphologic analysis, the mice were perfused with 0.9 % saline
followed by 4 % paraformaldehyde (PFA). And the brains were
removed and ﬁxed in 4 % PFA. For protein analysis, the mice were
isolated the hippocampus tissues and the hippocampus were
stored in 80 C.
2.2. Intraperitoneal glucose tolerance test (IPGTT) and insulin
tolerance test (ITT)
IPGTT and ITT were assessed at the 5th week during the drug
administration. For the IPGTT, mice were injected intraperitoneally
with glucose (2 g/kg body weight) after fasted for 6 h. The blood
glucose levels were measured with a blood glucose meter (Ruidien,
Jiangsu, China) at 0, 30, 60, 120 min by snipping the tails and the
