235
area under the curve (AUC) of the blood glucose versus time was
calculated.
For the ITT, mice were injected subcutaneously with insulin
(0.75 U/kg body weight (Jiangsu Wanbang Biochemistry Medicine
Co. Ltd., Xuzhou, China); after fasted for 6 h. The blood glucose
levels were measured with a blood glucose meter (Ruidien, Jiangsu,
China) at 0, 15, 30, 60, 120 min by snipping the tails and the area
under the curve (AUC) of the blood glucose versus time was
calculated.
2.3. Morris water maze (MWM)
Subsequently, MWM (Taimeng Technology, Chengdu, China)
tests were used to perform spatial learning and memory at the 6th
week during the drug administration. The test consisted of place
navigation and spatial probe test. The water maze apparatus was
comprised of a circular with 120 cm in diameter and 50 cm in
height, and was ﬁlled with water that was controlled at 22 ± 1 C.
The water maze area was divided into four equal quadrants and a
hidden platform (10 cm in diameter) was located in approximately
2 cm below the water surface at the center of one of the four
quadrants in the tank. The place navigation which consisted of four
trails per day was carried out from day 1e6. Each mouse was
allowed to swim freely to ﬁnd the hidden platform within 90 s. If
the mouse could ﬁnd the platform and remained on it over 5 s, the
test was terminated. And the time that each mouse spent to ﬁnd the
platform was recorded as escape latency. If the mouse could not
ﬁnd the platform within 90 s, it was guided to the platform and
kept it staying on platform for 15 s, simultaneously, the escape la-
tency was recorded as 90 s. The spatial probe test was conducted on
the 7th day. The hidden platform was removed and each mouse
freely swam in the tank within 90 s. The swimming time in the
effective was recorded.
2.4. Homeostasis model assessment of insulin resistance (HOMA-IR)
determination
After MWM test, 6 h fasting blood samples were obtained for
serum insulin and plasma glucose determinations in order to
calculate the HOMA-IR. Fasting blood samples were collected from
the retro-orbital artery and placed into an Eppendorf tube. Then
they were centrifuged at 3000 rpm/min for 15 min at room tem-
perature. Serum was stored at 80 C until the assay. The serum
insulin was detected by mouse insulin enzyme-linked immune
sorbent assay (ELISA) (Shanghai Elisa Biotech Co., Ltd. Shanghai,
China). The homeostasis model assessment of insulin resistance
(HOMA-IR) was calculated by the formula23: HOMA-IR ¼ FBG
(mmol/L)*fasting insulin (FINS, IU/mL)/22.5.
2.5. Transmission electron microscope (TEM)
The hippocampus were minced into 1 mm3 cubes and ﬁxed with
2.5 % glutaraldehyde and 2 % osmic acid, then dehydrated and
embedded in epoxy resin. Ultrathin sections were collected onto
200-mesh copper grids, double stained with uranyl acetate and
lead acetate, and then observed with a Hitachi H-7650 transmission
electron microscope (Hitachi, Tokyo, Japan).
2.6. Hematoxylin and eosin staining (HE staining)
Brains were ﬁxed in 4 % PFA for 24 h and embedded in parafﬁn.
Then rain tissue sections of 4 mm were obtained for HE staining.
Morphologic changes in hippocampal and cerebral cortical neurons
were observed using light microscopy (BX51, Olympus, Tokyo,
Japan) at 400 magniﬁcation.
2.7. Primary cortical neuron cultures
The method of primary cortical neuron culture was conducted
as previously described.24 Primary cortical neurons of rat were
prepared from E18 to E19 SpragueeDawley rat embryos. The
pregnant SD rat was anesthetized with 10 % chloral hydrate at a
dose of 3 mL/kg body weight. Then the embryos were removed to
isolate the brains. 5 to 7 embryos were used to isolate the brains for
our subsequent experiment. The cerebral cortices were dissected
from the brain in sterile ice cold PBS with the blood vessels and
meninges carefully removed. After being collected in a glass Petri
dish, all the cerebral cortices were cut into cubes of 1 mm3 and then
pipetted 20 times in 5 mL DMEM medium (Hyclone, USA). Undis-
persed pieces were ﬁltered through a nylon mesh with a pore size
of 75 mm, and then the supernatant was transferred to a new sterile
15 mL tube and centrifuged at 1000 rpm/min for 3 min at room
temperature. Cell aliquots were resuspended, and viable cells were
counted using a trypan blue dye exclusion assay. The single-cell
suspension was then cultured in a Neurobasal medium (Gibco
Invitrogen Corporation, Carlsbad, CA, USA) supplemented with 2 %
B27 supplement (Gibco Invitrogen Corporation, Carlsbad, CA, USA),
0.25 % GlutaMax (Gibco Invitrogen Corporation, Carlsbad, CA, USA),
0.5 % penicillin/streptomycin (Beijing Solarbio Science & Technol-
ogy Co., Ltd. Beijing, China). Then the cortical neurons were incu-
bated in 5 % CO2/95 % air at 37 C. And the cortical neurons were
plated on poly-L-ornithine hydrobromide-coated 96-well plate
(5  104 cells/well) for cell viability assay, and 6-well plate
(2  106 cells/well) for Western blots analysis. Half of the medium
was replaced by fresh medium every three days.
2.8. Cell viability assay
Cell counting kit-8 (CCK-8) (FDbio Science Biotech Co., Ltd.
Hangzhou, China) was used to determined cell viability. The cortical
neurons were plated on poly-L-ornithine hydrobromide-coated 96-
well plate (5  104 cells/well). After cultured for 7 d, the cortical
neurons were treated with Baﬁlomycin A1 (Baﬁlomycin A1 is most
known for its use as an autophagy inhibitor, which inhibited the
fusion of autophagosome and lysosome.) for 1 h in advance, then
were treated with glucose (50 mmol/L) and/or different concen-
trations of liraglutide (1, 10, 100, 500, 1000 mmol/L) for another
48 h.24 Subsequently, each well was treated with CCK-8 and the
plate was incubated in 5 % CO2/95 % air at 37 C for 2 h. The
absorbance at 450 nm was measured by monochromator micro-
plate reader. The optical density value equaled OD value.
2.9. Immunoﬂuorescence labeling
Brains were ﬁxed in 4% PFA for 24 h and embedded in parafﬁn.
The brain tissue sections of 4 mm were obtained for immunohis-
tochemistry. For heat-induced epitope retrieval, deparafﬁnized
sections were incubated in citrate buffer (Heart, China) at 98 C for
30 min by a microwave oven. After incubated with 3 % H2O2 for
20 min at room temperature, sections were washed using PBS.
Subsequently, sections were blocked with 5 % BSA for 2 h, followed
by treatment with rabbit anti-microtubule-associated protein light
1 chain (LC3B) monoclonal antibody (1:200, GeneTex, Inc., Irvine,
CA) at 4 C overnight. After washed with PBS, sections were treated
with goat anti-rabbit IgG (Alexa Fluor 488) (1:200, Zhuangzhi,
China) at room temperature for 2 h. Then sections were washed
using PBS, followed by mounting with DAPI (Beijing Solarbio Sci-
ence & Technology Co., Ltd. Beijing, China) nuclear counter stain-
ing. Stained cells were subsequently observed using an Olympus
BX-51 ﬂuorescence microscope (Olympus, Tokyo, Japan) at 400
magniﬁcation.
M. Zhang, W. Yan, Y. Yu et al.
Journal of Pharmacological Sciences 147 (2021) 234e244
236
2.10. Western blots analysis
Western blots were performed by the standard method.24 Brieﬂy,
the hippocampus tissue and cortical neurons (plated on poly-L-
ornithine hydrobromide-coated 96-well plate (2  106 cells/well)
were homogenized in RIPA lysate (Beyotime Institute of Biotech-
nology, Xi'an, China) containing protease inhibitor (Roche, Basel,
Switzerland) with an electric homogenizer (Kinematica, Swiss), then
processed by ultrasonic disruptor (Sonics, Newtown, USA). After
incubated on ice for 15 min and clariﬁed by centrifugation at
16,000g for 15 min at 4 C. The supernatants were obtained and the
concentrations of all samples were measured by BCA protein assay
kit (Beijing Solarbio Science & Technology Co., Ltd. Beijing, China).
Then 20e30 mg of protein from each sample was loaded into 8%e
15 % SDS-PAGE gels electrophoresis. After electrophoresis, the pro-
teins were transferred to PVDF membranes (Millipore, MA, USA).
After blocked with 5 % non-fat milk at room temperature for 2 h, the
membranes were incubated with primary antibody against LC3B
(1:1500, GeneTex, Inc., Irvine, CA), P62/SQSTM1 (1:1500, Proteintech
Group, Chicago, USA), Beclin1 (1:1000, Cell Signaling Technology,
USA), Ab (1:1500, Abcam, UK), Lysosome-associated membrane
protein (LAMP-2) (1:1000, Thermo Fisher Scientiﬁc, USA), GLP-1R
(1:1000, Abcam, UK) and GAPDH (1:10,000, Proteintech Group,
Chicago, USA) at 4 C overnight. Next day, the membranes were
washed 10 min with TBST for 3 times and subsequently incubated
with corresponding HRP-conjugated secondary antibodies at room
temperature for 2 h. After washed for another 3 times in TBST, pro-
tein bands were detected with Super-Lumia ECL Plus HRP Substrate
Kit solution (Abbkine; Redlands, CA, USA) by chemiluminescence
imaging system (UVP, Upland, USA) and the band intensity were
quantiﬁed by using ImageJ.
2.11. Statistical analysis
Data were analyzed by using SPSS 18.0 software. All the results
were expressed as mean ± standard error of mean (SEM). Differ-
ences between groups were analyzed by using one-way ANOVA
test. If data were showed normally distributed, pairwise compari-
sons were conducted by LSD test. If not, pairwise comparisons were
conducted by Dunnett T3 test. The escape latency in Morris water
maze was analyzed by MANOVA (multivariate analysis of variance)
of repeated measures for comparisons among trials. All P values
were two-sided, and a value of P less than 0.05 were considered as
statistically signiﬁcant.
3. Results
3.1. Effects of liraglutide on BW and FBG levels of T2DM mice
After successfully establishing T2DM model, the BW and FBG
levels in control, T2DM and liraglutide groups were determined
weekly during 6 weeks of drug treatment. As shown in Fig. 1A, the
BW of control, T2DM and liraglutide groups didn't show any sig-
niﬁcant difference. FBG was measured after fasted for 6 h. As shown
in Fig. 1B, compared with the control group, signiﬁcantly increased
FBG levels were observed in T2DM group (P < 0.01). Compared with
T2DM group, liraglutide could signiﬁcantly decrease the FBG in
T2DM mice (P < 0.01).
3.2. Effects of liraglutide on IPGTT and ITT of T2DM mice
IPGTT and ITT are widely used to evaluate the glucose and insulin
tolerance. As shown in Fig. 1. In IPGTT, T2DM mice manifested a
higher glucose load at baseline and a strongly elevated load
following glucose administration compared with the control group
(Fig. 1C, P < 0.01). The glucose load was decreased much more
promptly and persisted in the mice treated with liraglutide, as
compared to the T2DM group (Fig.1C, P < 0.01). The AUC of the IPGTT
in the model group was signiﬁcantly increased than those in the
control group (Fig. 1D, P < 0.01). However, the AUC of IPGTT in the
liraglutide group was signiﬁcantly lower than those in the T2DM
group (Fig. 1D, P < 0.01). In the ITT, the blood glucose levels were
rapidly decreased within 60 min and increased at 120 min after the
insulin injection in all groups. Compared with T2DM group, the
blood glucose levels in liraglutide group were signiﬁcantly decreased
at 0, 15, and 30 min after insulin injection (Fig. 1E, P < 0.01), while
they were still higher than that in control group (Fig. 1E, P < 0.01).
Furthermore, the AUC of T2DM mice was signiﬁcantly higher than
that of control mice (Fig. 1F, P < 0.01). The AUC of liraglutide group
was lower than the T2DM group (Fig. 1F, P < 0.01). Altogether, these
data indicated that liraglutide could ameliorate the impaired glucose
and insulin tolerance in T2DM mice.
3.3. Effects of liraglutide on serum insulin levels and insulin
resistance
Insulin plays an important role in glucose regulation, so the
effects of liraglutide on serum insulin levels were investigated. As
shown in Fig. 1G, the T2DM mice showed obviously increased
serum insulin levels compared with the control mice (Fig. 1G,
P < 0.01), and treatment with liraglutide signiﬁcantly reduced
serum insulin levels (Fig. 1G, P < 0.01). Subsequently, HOMA-IR was
assayed to examine the insulin sensitivity in these groups. HOMA-
IR of T2DM group was markedly increased compared with control
group (Fig. 1H, P < 0.01). However, liraglutide could ameliorate the
insulin resistance in T2DM mice (Fig. 1H, P < 0.05).
3.4. Liraglutide ameliorates the learning and memory impairments
in T2DM mice
We next evaluated the effect of liraglutide on the spatial
learning and memory by using MWM test. As shown in Fig. 2,
compared with control group, T2DM group showed a signiﬁcantly
increased escape latency during the place navigation acquisition
from day 3 to day 6 (Fig. 2A, P < 0.01). In probe trail, the T2DM mice
spent less time in the effective area (Fig. 2B, P < 0.01). Whereas, the
mice treated with liraglutide found the hidden platform more
quickly (Fig. 2A, P < 0.01) and spent more time in the effective area
(Fig. 2B, P < 0.05) compared with T2DM group. Collectively, the
results suggested that T2DM mice showed a cognitive deﬁcit, while
liraglutide ameliorated the impaired spatial learning and memory
ability in T2DM mice.
3.5. Liraglutide alleviates hippocampal neuronal injuries and
synaptic ultrastructural degradation in T2DM mice
The hippocampus, a key brain region responsible for learning
and memory, is vulnerable to changes in glucose homeostasis. The
structure of hippocampal neurons in T2DM mice was observed by
HE staining and TEM. The representative graphs of neuronal
morphology in each group were shown in Fig. 3. The hippocampal
regions CA1 in the mice from each group were stained with HE. The
nuclei showing pyknosis were deeply stained and lost and the
neurons arrangement became obviously disordered in hippocam-
pal CA1 regions of T2DM mice compared with the control group.
Additionally, liraglutide signiﬁcantly ameliorated the pathologic
changes in T2DM mice. According to the TEM results, the hippo-
campal neurons in T2DM mice showed severe degenerative
changes, including the decline in the number of neurons, swelling
and dilatation of Golgi complex, blurred or vacuolated cristae of
M. Zhang, W. Yan, Y. Yu et al.
Journal of Pharmacological Sciences 147 (2021) 234e244
237
mitochondria and synaptic morphometry changes (Fig. 3E, P < 0.01)
compared with control group. However, the ultrastructure of
neurons in liraglutide treatment was improved to varying degrees.
Collectively, these observations indicated that liraglutide reduced
the pathological degeneration and improved the ultrastructure of
neurons.
3.6. Liraglutide prevents autophagic ﬂux impairment and reduces
Ab deposition in T2DM mice
To conﬁrm whether liraglutide exerted its protective roles in
learning and memory in T2DM mice via preventing autophagic ﬂux
impairment and reducing Ab deposition, Western blots assay and
immunoﬂuorescence labeling were used to detect the expressions
of related proteins. The results showed that LC3BII/I ratio (Fig. 4A,
P < 0.01) and Beclin1 protein expression (Fig. 4B, P < 0.05) were
signiﬁcantly decreased, while p62 protein expression (Fig. 4C,
P < 0.01) was increased in T2DM group compared with those of
control group. These results indicated autophagic ﬂux dysfunction
occurred in T2DM mice. Notably, liraglutide could increase LC3BII/I
ratio (Fig. 4A, P < 0.01) and Beclin1 protein expression (Fig. 4B,
P < 0.05), and decrease p62 protein expression (Fig. 4C, P < 0.01) in
T2DM mice. The results suggested that liraglutide could ameliorate
autophagic ﬂux dysfunction.
