neurons was recovered to more than 90 % (Fig. 5A, P < 0.05), and
treatment with liraglutide alone did not affect the primary cortical
neurons (Fig. 5B, P < 0.05). Then we chose 100 nmol/L liraglutide for
use in subsequence experiments.
3.8. Liraglutide protects primary cortical neurons by ameliorating
autophagic ﬂux
Autophagic ﬂux is controlled by the balance between autopha-
gosome formation and autophagic degradation. To investigate
whether liraglutide could ameliorate the damaged autophagic ﬂux
in HG-induced primary cortical neurons, we used Western blots
assay and immunocytochemistry labeling to detect the expressions
of related proteins. Results showed LC3BII/I ratio (Fig. 6A, P < 0.01)
and Beclin1 protein expression (Fig. 6B, P<0.05) were signiﬁcantly
decreased, while p62 protein expression (Fig. 6C, P < 0.01) was
increased in HG-induced primary cortical neurons compared with
those of control group. These results indicated autophagic ﬂux
dysfunction occurred in HG-induced primary cortical neurons.
However, liraglutide could signiﬁcantly increase LC3BII/I ratio
(Fig. 6A, P < 0.01) and Beclin1 protein expression (Fig. 6B, P < 0.05),
while decrease p62 protein expression(Fig. 6C, P < 0.01), which
indicated that liraglutide could recuse the autophagic ﬂux in HG-
induced primary cortical neurons. Compared with control group,
LAMP-2 protein expression (which is associated with lysosome)
was signiﬁcantly decreased (Fig. 6D, P < 0.01) in HG-induced pri-
mary cortical neurons. However, liraglutide could signiﬁcantly in-
crease LAMP-2 protein expression (Fig. 6D, P < 0.01). Liraglutide
ameliorated the function of lysosome.
To determine whether the protective effects of liraglutide on
HG-induced primary cortical neurons were mediated through
improved lysosome function, the primary cortical neurons were
treated with Baﬁlomycin A1. Baﬁlomycin A1 is most known for its
use as an autophagy inhibitor, which inhibited the fusion of auto-
phagosome and lysosome. As shown in Fig. 6A-D, Baﬁlomycin A1
markedly increased LC3BII/I ratio and the expression of p62 protein
and decreased the expression of LAMP-2 protein, although the
expression of Beclin1 was not signiﬁcantly changed. In addition,
Baﬁlomycin A1 partially abolished the effects of liraglutide. Baﬁ-
lomycin A1 evidently prevented the fusion of autophagosome and
lysosome.
4. Discussion
T2DM is a global health problem with the increased risk of de-
mentia.25,26 Multiple population-based studies have reported an
association between T2DM and cognitive impairment. With regard
to speciﬁc cognitive domains, associations between T2DM or in-
sulin resistance are most commonly reported with both episodic
memory and
decreased
executive
function,
including
verbal
ﬂuency, working memory, processing speed, cognitive ﬂexibility,
and cognitive control.27e29 However, effective clinical drugs to
prevent this decline are very limited. The GLP-1 analog liraglutide
has been recognized as the important drug for T2DM. In addition to
exerting beneﬁcial effects at pancreatic sites, liraglutide has also
been shown to exert neuroprotective effects on some neurode-
generative disease, including AD, PD, Huntington's disease (HD) or
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, stroke.30e33 In our study, we evalu-
ated the beneﬁcial effect of liraglutide on learning and memory and
explored its underlying mechanisms in T2DM mice with cognitive
dysfunction and HG-induced rat primary cortical neurons. The
ﬁnding was that treatment with liraglutide alleviated cognitive
decline, reduced hippocampal and synaptic ultrastructure injuries,
decreased the accumulation of Ab in hippocampus of T2DM mice.
Furthermore, we found that liraglutide prevented the development
of T2DM cognitive dysfunction by restoring the damaged auto-
phagic ﬂux, including reducing the accumulation of autophago-
somes and increasing the fusion of autophagosome and lysosome
in vivo and vitro. These ﬁndings suggested that liraglutide can be
exploited as a potential therapeutic reagent for the improvement of
diabetic-associated cognitive impairment.
T2DM is an endocrine and metabolic disorder disease, which is
characterized by hyperglycemia and insulin resistance.34 Therefore,
improving insulin resistance and glucose levels have been consid-
ered as a principal strategy to treat T2DM. Insulin plays an impor-
tant role in blood glucose homeostasis. Under the insulin resistance
conditions, insulin cannot play an effective role in promoting
glucose uptake, thereby leading to an excessive increase in the in-
sulin secretion. Such compensatory hyperinsulinemia is probably
the cause of many other disorders such as hyperglycemia and
dyslipidemia.35,36 In the present study, we found that the treatment
with liraglutide has little effect on the body weight, but signiﬁ-
cantly decreased FBG in T2DM mice. Results of serum insulin test
revealed that the treatment with liraglutide could decrease the
serum insulin levels and HOMA-IR in T2DM mice. IPGTT and ITT
results showed liraglutide could ameliorate glucose tolerance and
insulin sensitivity in T2DM mice. All the results were consistent
with previous studies.37,38 Chronic hyperglycemia and insulin
resistance are regarded as major causes for T2DM and its compli-
cations, triggering progressive structural and functional abnor-
malities of brain.39,40 Interestingly, it has been proved that GLP-1 is
a good candidate for improving cognitive dysfunction in diabetes-
induced dementia, related to controlling glycemic homeostasis
and insulin resistance.41 Based on these data, we inferred the
Fig. 5. Liraglutide attenuates HG-induced primary cortical neurons damage. (A) The effects of different concentrations of liraglutide on HG-induced primary cortical neurons
damage. (B) The effects of 100 nmol/L liraglutide on the cell viability of primary cortical neurons treated with or without HG. The cell viability was measured by CCK-8 kit. Data are
expressed as mean ± SEM, n ¼ 4. **P < 0.01, versus Control; #P < 0.05, ##P < 0.01, versus HG.
M. Zhang, W. Yan, Y. Yu et al.
Journal of Pharmacological Sciences 147 (2021) 234e244
241
amelioration of cognitive impairments achieved by liraglutide was
associated with improved glycemic homeostasis and insulin resis-
tance to some extent.
Accumulating evidences have conﬁrmed diabetes have been
regarded as an independent risk factor for AD. Diabetes-associated
cognitive dysfunction has gained widespread attention for its
deleterious impact on individuals with diabetes.6,42 As the safest
therapy for T2DM, the neuroprotective effects of GLP-1 analogs
have been widely discussed in patients with metabolic disorder.
Previous studies have shown that GLP-1 analogs slow down the
progression of cognitive decline in different animal models.13,15,43
Learning and memory are two vital components of cognitive
function. In our previous research, liraglutide could improve
learning and memory in T1DM mice reﬂected by improved per-
formance on Morris water maze task. In addition, it revealed that
liraglutide treatment reduced hippocampal and synaptic injuries,
protected against oxidative and inhibited neuronal apoptosis
through PI3K/Akt signaling pathway.13 In our current study, we
found that liraglutide treatment could markedly decrease the
escape latency and increase the time in the effective area in MWM
test in T2DM mice. Hippocampus is an important brain region
which plays a key role in learning and memory. And the hippo-
campal neuronal injuries partially lead to the impaired learning and
memory.44 Synapse is essential for functional connection between
neurons and signal transmission, and synaptic plasticity is thought
to be cellular mechanisms of learning and memory.45 In our present
study, liraglutide treatment improved the damaged neuronal
morphology in the hippocampal CA1 region. Meanwhile, TEM ob-
servations suggested that liraglutide protected cognitive impair-
ment in T2DM mice by reducing neuronal and synaptic injuries.
These results indicated that liraglutide showed a potential in
ameliorating cognitive deﬁcit in T2DM.
Extracellular amyloid plaques, which are markedly pathological
features of AD, are composed of an insoluble aggregation of Ab. And
Fig. 6. Liraglutide protects primary cortical neurons by ameliorating autophagic ﬂux. (A) The expression of LC3B protein. (B) The expression of Beclin1 protein. (C) The expression of
p62 protein. (D) The expression of LAMP-2 protein. In Western blots, data are expressed as mean ± SEM, n ¼ 5. *P < 0.05, **P < 0.01, versus Control; #P < 0.05, ##P < 0.01, versus HG;
&P < 0.05, &&P < 0.01, versus liraglutide group without Baﬁlomycin A1. Baﬁlomycin A1 is an autophagy inhibitor, which inhibited the fusion of autophagosome and lysosome.
M. Zhang, W. Yan, Y. Yu et al.
Journal of Pharmacological Sciences 147 (2021) 234e244
242
the deposition of Ab is hypothesized to initiate a pathological
cascade leading to AD, which can cause neuron necrosis, apoptosis
and amyloidosis, and peripheral insulin resistance.31,46 A few
studies also showed that T2DM patients exhibited impaired insulin
signaling pathways accompanied with increased Ab accumula-
tion.47 Notably, GLP-1 analogs such as liraglutide and exendin-4
attenuate endogenous levels of Ab in the brain and prevent Ab
accumulation in the AD brain.21,48 But few studies have clariﬁed
whether liraglutide could attenuate the Ab accumulation in hip-
pocampus of T2DM. In the current study, we found that liraglutide
could signiﬁcantly reduce the Ab accumulation in hippocampus of
T2DM. Ab over-deposition can mediate oxidative stress, mito-
chondrial damage and DNA fragmentation.21,49 Therefore, we
assumed that Ab accumulation could cause neuronal injury, which
would further result in learning and memory in T2DM mice.
Interestingly, Ma et al. conﬁrmed autophagy-lysosome dysfunction
may be involved in the Ab over-deposition in STZ-induced diabetic
cognitive dysfunction.50 In accordance with this, we further dis-
cussed the possible mechanisms underlying neuroprotective ef-
fects of liraglutide through modulating autophagic ﬂux.
Autophagy
plays
critical
roles
in
cellular
self-digestion
pathway that is responsible for the systematic degradation and
recycling of harmful components, such as protein aggregates and
impaired organelles, which is essential for neuronal homeosta-
sis.51 Autophagy impairment is associated with multiple diseases
including diabetes-related disease, which was activated exces-
sively or inhibited.52,53 Meanwhile, autophagy is common in many
neurodegenerative disorders including AD, PD and diabetes-
associated cognitive impairment.49,50 Autophagy is a dynamic
process
including
induction,
autophagosome
formation,
the
fusion of autophagosome with lysosome to form autolysosome,
and ﬁnal digestion by proteases to generate amino acids and en-
ergy. Autophagic ﬂux is controlled by the balance between auto-
phagosome
formation
and
autophagic
degradation.
In
the
healthy brain, autophagy is active and the clearance of the
autophagosomal-lysosomal pathway is highly efﬁcient to prevent
autophagic
substrate
accumulation.
Then
autophagic
ﬂux
dysfunction is closely related to diabetes-associated cognitive
dysfunction that shows abnormally aggregated proteins.50,54 It
should be noted that GLP-1 analogs also exert a neuroprotective
effect via modulating autophagic ﬂux. Kong and her group found
that liraglutide ameliorates cognitive decline by promoting
autophagy via the AMPK/PI3K pathway in T1DM.15 Candeias et al.
reported that brain GLP-1/IGF-1 signaling and autophagy medi-
ated exendin-4 protection against apoptosis in T2DM rats.55 Yang
concluded that the protective effects of liraglutide may be asso-
ciated with autophagy via activation of the AMPK and PI3K/Akt
signaling pathways.22 In line with these studies, we found that
treatment with liraglutide restored the impaired neuronal auto-
phagic ﬂux in vivo and in vitro. LC3B is a biomarker for autophagic
structures. LC3BeI is distributed homogeneously with the cyto-
plasm. On the other hand, LC3B-II is bound to both sides of the
autophagosomal double membrane. As autophagy is active, the
alteration in the ratio of LC3B-II/I indicates changes in autophagy
activity. Beclin1 is part of a lipid kinase complex, playing a central
role in autophagy. Autophagy might stimulate the expression of
Beclin1. Generally, accumulation of p62 has been used as a marker
for autophagy inhibition. LAMP-2 is a critical component of lyso-
somal membrane, playing a role in mediating autophagy vacuoles
and lysosomal fusion.56 In our current study, T2DM mice and HG-
induced rat primary cortical neurons showed a decreased ratio of
LC3BII/Iand expression of Beclin1 and LAMP-2, but an elevated
expression of p62 in hippocampus, indicating the autophagy was
inhibited. However, liraglutide could reverse the changes, which
is consistent with previous research.22 Furthermore, compared
with the liraglutide treatment in HG-induced rat primary cortical
neurons without Baﬁlomycin A1, the lysosomes were impaired in
HG-induced rat primary cortical neurons when co-treated with
Baﬁlomycin A1, as revealed the expression of LAMP-2 protein
signiﬁcantly decreased compared with liraglutide treatment.
Subsequently, damaged lysosomes could not fuse with autopha-
gosomes, which caused autophagosomes accumulation. These
results revealed liraglutide treatment signiﬁcantly reversed lyso-
somal defects and increased the clearance of autophagosomes
(LC3BII/I ratio signiﬁcantly increased compared with liraglutide
treatment), which suggested that the protective effects of lir-
aglutide on HG-induced rat primary cortical neurons were closely
associated with autophagic ﬂux. Our results were consistent with
exendin-4
on
autophagy
clearance
in b
cell
of
rats
with
tacrolimus-induced diabetes mellitus.57 Therefore, our results
revealed liraglutide activated autophagy but did not lead to
autophagy clearance disorder, and increased the lysosomal func-
tion of the fusion of autophagosomes and lysosomes.
Autophagy is the key way to clear over-produced protein or
abnormal organelles. Ma et al. showed Ab deposition may be
related to autophagy-lysosome dysfunction. However, another
possible result of diabetes-induced Ab deposition in the hippo-
campus is that Ab deposition
leads to autophagy-lysosome
impairment, creating a vicious circle.50 In our study, liraglutide
might reduce the Ab deposition in the hippocampus via preventing
the autophagy-lysosome impairment in T2DM. However, more
researches are needed to study the speciﬁc mechanisms in the
future. The crosstalk between lysosomal function, autophagy-
lysosome and Ab, and its underlying molecular mechanism,
should be investigated. And the colocalization of Ab, LC3B and
LAMP-2 awaits further study. Additionally the relationship be-
tween decreasing blood glucose, ameliorating autophagy ﬂux and
reducing Ab of the liraglutide treatment is still need to be discussed
in diabetes-associated cognitive dysfunction.
In conclusion, these above observations suggested that the
neuroprotective effects of liraglutide on cognitive dysfunction,
hippocampal neuronal injuries and Ab deposition appear to be
related to restoring the autophagic ﬂux. These ﬁndings enhance
our
understanding
of
liraglutide-mediated
neuroprotection
against diabetes-associated cognitive impairment. Our results
suggest that liraglutide may provide potential therapeutic strat-
egy for preventing cognitive defect in T2DM. Although accumu-
lating studies have indicated that effective anti-diabetic agents
are also promising therapeutic interventions to prevent cognitive
disorders,58 these hypoglycemic agents have some shortcomings
in the treatment of diabetic cognitive dysfunction. Metformin or
sulfonylureas are difﬁcult to maintain stable blood glucose level
for a long time, and the long-term use of insulin may lead to hy-
poglycemia, which might deteriorate the cognitive function.59
Liraglutide, as a GLP-1 analog, is different from conventional hy-
poglycemic drugs. It stimulates insulin secretion and inhibit
glucagon production in a glucose-dependent manner without
prompting hypoglycemia. In this regard, liraglutide is more
effective and possibly safer than those conventional anti-diabetic
drugs.
